<br>
With respect to Complete Heal, those druids who want this spell are definitely in the minority in this community.  I'm in the opposite minority, actually.  I don't think that asking to be a better secondary healer is in the best interest of the druid class.  Secondary healer is a dead end job.  Why bring a druid to a raid for that purpose when you could bring a cleric who can not only do a better job of it, but can be used on some other raid as a primary healer?  Bringing a druid to a raid instead of another cleric is much like bringing a mage to a raid instead of another wizard, except that the scaling is far worse.  10:1 CH vs. NT, as compared to 2:1, more or less, on mage vs. wizard nukes.  The salvation of the druid class must be found in capabilities other than healing.<br>
<br>
As for the epic...  You're coming from the perspective of the Mage epic.  The Mage epic is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  hard</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Way too hard, really.  That doesn't really mean that the druid epic is somehow trivially easy, however, and thus unworthy of a decent effect.  Take a look at the shaman and rogue epics sometime if you want a basis for comparison.  Those are also &quot;easy&quot;, and they're not subject to the same sort of devaluation that comes from the druid epic being overwritten by the necro epic or being useless on the ever increasing numbers of mobs that are immune to movement speed changes.<br>
<br>
Griping...  There's lots of griping from lots of classes.  It is interesting to visit lots of class boards and see what the noise level is.  There seems to be clear inverse correlation between the amount of ranting on a class board and the usefulness of that class in the end game.  Which makes perfect sense, really.<br>
<br>
This is probably the wrong place to come with concerns about dire charm.  The druid dire charm is the least useful version by far since it only affects animals, yet if druids want this skill, they have to pay just as much for it in terms of AA as enchanters and necros, both of whom (enchanters in particular) get more use out of it.  Mages did end up pretty big losers when it came to AA skills, though.  I'll certainly conceed that, and I definitely support you and your fellow mages when it comes to getting improvements in that area.<br>
<br>
Anti-summoned...  Well, ask yourself why clerics get this spell line, and I think you'll be closer to understanding why druids get it before mages.  The basic idea of the spell line is an &quot;anti-unnatural&quot; spell.  I'm speculating the thought process at Verant during the game design days went something like this:  What creatures are unnatural?  Well, undead are unnatural, but they're also the domain of clerics and paladins--can't give druids that!  What else is unnatural?  Oh, yes.  Summoned stuff is unnatural.  Let's give druids that!  Wait, these mobs are summoned, shouldn't mages get this spell line?  Sure, but since it's a druid spell line, they should get it later.  Hey, shouldn't clerics get anti-unnatural spells too?  Why sure, let's give the same spell line to clerics. (Ignores that clerics already get anti-unnatural in the form of anti-undead).<br>
<br>
